17_9	0.0	In the study in Thursday's issue of the journal Nature, Wentz found that the orbit of satellites that take temperature readings decreases over time because of atmospheric drag on the spacecraft.
17_10	0.0	They drop a bit more than half a mile (about a kilometer) every year, and twice that during some years.
17_11	0.0	As the satellite slows and drops, the onboard instrument perceives the temperatures below it as cooling, Wentz found.
17_12	0.0	The perceived temperature change ``was just an artifact of the altitude changing,'' he concluded.
17_13	0.38095238095238093	When Wentz recalculated the readings from 1979 to 1995, he found temperatures in the lower atmosphere are more in line with rising temperatures at Earth's surface and rising temperatures just a few miles (kilometers) higher in the atmosphere.
17_14	0.05405405405405406	Before the correction, scientists were confounded because temperatures in the lower troposphere, the region from the ground to about two miles (3.2 kilometers) up, seemed to be cooling.09 degrees Fahrenheit (0.05 degrees Celsius) per decade, while the middle to upper troposphere _ a region centered about four miles (6.4 kilometers) up _ seemed to be warming .05 degrees Fahrenheit (0.03 degrees Celsius) every decade.
17_15	0.10526315789473684	But when Wentz and co-author Matthias Schabel took the falling satellite effect into account, they found the lower troposphere was warming 0.13 degrees Fahrenheit (0.07 Celsius) per decade.
