18_2	0.125	Researchers said that the growing season over this period has therefore lengthened by 10.8 days on average.
18_3	1.875	They said that the changes are caused by a temperature increase, which is one of the effects of global warming.
19_0	0.75	A study of changes in wind patterns linked to global warming over the past 50 years suggests they are slowing the planet's daily spin by around half a millisecond every century.
19_1	1.2307692307692308	These effects open up a new way of tracking the progress of global warming without the uncertainties in simple temperature measurements.
19_2	0.06666666666666667	Ocean currents associated with El Nio are already known to make equatorial winds blow faster and boost the angular momentum of the atmosphere.
19_3	0.45454545454545453	Momentum must be conserved, so the atmosphere steals momentum from the Earth's rotation, making it spin more slowly.
19_4	0.0	Satellite observations showed that last year's El Nio made days drag on by an extra 0.4 milliseconds.
19_5	1.875	Climate experts have suspected that steady global warming might have a similar effect.
19_6	0.47058823529411764	Computer models of the effects of warming point to the appearance of jets of fast-moving wind between the troposphere and stratosphere, roughly 12 kilometers above the Earth's surface.
19_7	0.2222222222222222	These would also boost the angular momentum of the atmosphere, triggering a compensating slowing down in the Earth.
19_8	0.0	Now Rodrigo Abarca del Rio of the French space agency's Toulouse Space Center has looked for direct evidence of this.
19_9	0.5833333333333334	Over the past 50 years, the Earth's average temperature has been increasing by around 0.79 C per century.
19_10	0.0	Using wind data for the same period from the U.S.
19_11	0.07692307692307693	National Centers for Atmospheric Research and Environmental Prediction, Abarca del Rio calculated the angular momentum of the atmosphere.
19_12	0.38461538461538464	He found it had increased in step with the temperature rise ''There has also been a net loss in angular momentum by the solid Earth,'' he says.
19_13	1.5	''The data suggest that global warming has caused a slowdown of the Earth at a rate of 0.56 milliseconds a century''.
19_14	2.0833333333333335	This implies that global warming is responsible for almost one-third of the slowing down in the Earth's spin scientists have measured.
19_15	1.875	It also suggests that the length of the day could provide a means of monitoring global warming in future.
19_16	0.0	Every 0.1 degree C increase should produce a slowdown of 0.07 milliseconds, which is easy to measure.
19_17	0.375	However, Abarca del Rio says too many other complex effects influence the Earth's spin, such as movement of molten rock beneath its surface.
19_18	0.25	Instead, he suggests using records on atmospheric angular momentum, which have been kept since the mid-1970s.
19_19	1.25	''Records of surface air temperature have been the main measure of global warming,'' says Abarca del Rio.
19_20	0.2857142857142857	''Measurements of atmospheric angular momentum may be an easier and more reliable way''.
19_21	1.0666666666666667	Masaki Satoh, a climate modeler at Saitama Institute of Technology in Japan, agrees that the results could provide a new and better way to monitor global warming.
19_22	1.5454545454545454	''Atmospheric angular momentum is increased by the El Nio event, so it is reasonable that it should also increase with global warming''.
